PART VIII: THE VAULTS

The Boom

The tunnel descended from the Warrens in a steep, slick-stoned grade that smelled of standing water and old iron. Mila walked between Saijah and Alfonso, her hand still locked around Saijah's, her eyes tracking every sound. She had never been this deep. She had lived her entire life in the Warrens and she had never gone past the bottom passage because the residents who went past the bottom passage sometimes didn't come back.

She was walking past it now, because the Lanterns were walking past it, and Saijah's hand was warm.

The boom came from below.

Not an echo. Not the settling of old stone. A deliberate, concentrated impact ΓÇö the sound of something reinforced being forced. It shook dust from the ceiling in a thin curtain and sent ripples through the water pooled on the floor.

Then a second boom, closer, and the muffled consonants of a language that hit Saijah's new senses like ground glass ΓÇö Aldmeris, clipped and authoritative, the cadence of someone issuing orders to subordinates who were expected to obey without question.

Alfonso stopped walking. He turned to Mila with the clinical efficiency of a man assessing a problem.

He had no face for gentleness ΓÇö the Jagged Crown sat fused to his skull, the corroded rapier hung at his hip, and whatever softness might have once lived in his expression had long since been metabolised into something more useful. But he knelt to Mila's level, and his voice was even, and that was almost the same thing.

"I need you to be very still," he said. "And very quiet. Can you do that?"

Mila looked at him with enormous eyes. She nodded.

Alfonso's hand moved ΓÇö a precise, deliberate gesture, the plague-mage's architecture assembling itself from the residue of ten thousand infections. Ash and memory. The shell that formed around Mila was thin, grey, nearly invisible ΓÇö a carapace of hardened contagion shaped to the outline of a child, sealed at every seam. It would not stop a dragon. It would stop fire. It would stop a fireball detonating at close range, in a narrow corridor, with no cover.

Mila looked at her hands inside the shell. She looked up at Alfonso.

"Don't move," he said again. "Whatever happens."

She pressed herself against the tunnel wall and did not move.

They went down.

The Kill Shot

The Thalmor were sixty feet ahead when the party cleared the last bend ΓÇö four figures in the glow of magelight, three in armour forming a wall, the fourth behind them with a staff raised and the blue-white light orbiting his head like a captive moon. His free hand was pressed against a heavy iron-banded door. The frost cracking across its surface was visible from fifty feet.

He hadn't broken through yet. He had seconds left.

Saijah's bow was in her hand before she registered deciding to raise it. The predator senses ΓÇö Hircine's gift, unwanted and exact ΓÇö mapped the corridor instantly. Every heartbeat. Every breath. The wizard's pulse was fast and bright with concentration, the specific rhythm of a mage channelling power through a staff toward a focused point. She could hear the charge building in the weapon. The frequency of it. The way the air tightened around the tip as the spell prepared to fire.

He was going to shoot, and then he was going to open the door, and then the old man inside was going to die.

She loosed.

The arrow crossed sixty feet in the time it took the wizard to begin his turn. It caught the staff at the crystal focus ΓÇö not the man, the weapon, the exact point where the charged spell was housed ΓÇö and the contained lightning detonated in a sphere of white-hot discharge.

The wizard died in the flash. The two Justiciars nearest him died a half-second later. The third was thrown backward by the pressure wave, slammed against the far wall, and did not get up.

The magelight died with its caster. The corridor went black.

In the silence that followed, Saijah's new senses filled the darkness like water filling a vessel ΓÇö four heartbeats gone, the standing water still vibrating, the smell of scorched metal and burned wool hanging in the cold air. And from behind the door, ragged and terrified and alive: an old man breathing.

They had made it.

The Fangs

Orion moved through the aftermath the way he moved through everything ΓÇö quiet, unhurried, his ring burning cold against his finger. He checked the Thalmor for valuables with professional thoroughness. The staff was destroyed, but the rest of the equipment was salvageable. He noted the sealed orders on the wizard's body and pocketed them without reading them aloud.

Mila had followed them down when the sounds stopped. She shouldn't have ΓÇö Alfonso had told her to stay ΓÇö but she was eight years old and had been left alone in a dark tunnel while people she'd known for an hour went to fight monsters, and she had decided, with the pragmatic courage of a child who had grown up in the Warrens, that staying alone in the dark was worse than following.

She was standing in the mouth of the corridor when Orion turned around.

He looked at her. The corridor was still dark ΓÇö the magelight was gone, the only illumination coming from whatever light the party carried. In the shadows, his face was a pale composition of planes and angles, and his eyes caught the light the wrong way, and when he smiled, he smiled slowly, with his lips parting wide enough to show the canines.

Not the accidental exposure of a man who had forgotten to hide what he was. A deliberate presentation. Here is what I am, the smile said. Here is what I could do to you.

Mila made a sound that wasn't quite a word. She pressed herself back against the tunnel wall.

Saijah was between them before the sound finished ΓÇö not aggressive, not loud, just present, her body in the space Orion's gaze had been crossing. She put her hand on Mila's shoulder without looking down. Her eyes were on Orion.

Orion met them. The smile stayed. He turned back to the bodies.

Davinia had seen it from four feet away. Alfonso had seen it from six. Neither of them said anything. There was nothing to say that the silence didn't already say more precisely.

Mila's hand found Saijah's wrist and locked around it. Her grip was hard for a child her size. Her heartbeat ΓÇö audible to Saijah in the dark ΓÇö did not slow for a long time.

She would not go near Orion again. Not willingly. Not without being put there. The Warrens had taught her that some dangers announce themselves with raised voices and breaking doors, and some dangers smile at you from the dark, and the ones that smile are the ones you don't survive.

Esbern

The key from the dead drop fit the third lock. Three disengagements, sequential, the door swinging inward on hinges that had been oiled recently ΓÇö the only well-maintained thing in the entire Ratway.

The room behind it was a cell that had been lived in for thirty years. Maps on every surface. Charcoal diagrams of dragon anatomy annotated in a cramped, obsessive hand. Books stacked from the floor in columns ΓÇö a paper forest, dense and particular. A cot. A desk buried under documents. A cold plate of untouched bread and cheese.

An old man stood at the center of it. Perhaps seventy. Long grey beard. Eyes enormous behind cracked reading spectacles. He held a dagger in one shaking hand and a lit torch in the other.

He stared at them. He was deciding whether they were the reason the door had stayed closed or the reason it had finally opened.

"You're the Lanterns." His voice cracked on the second word. "The ones from Kynesgrove. From the Pale." He searched their faces. "My agent ΓÇö Caius ΓÇö he was supposed to be hereΓÇö"

He read the answer before anyone spoke. The dagger lowered. The torch lowered. He sat on the cot with the specific, folding descent of a man whose body has just received news his mind hasn't finished processing.

"Ah," he said.

They gave him Caius's letter. He read it in silence, his hands steady in a way the rest of him wasn't. When he looked up his eyes were wet and his voice was even.

"He found it," Esbern said. "Alduin's Wall. He found it and they killed him for it."

He looked at them across thirty years of paper and preparation and hiding.

"I have been in this room since the Great War ended. I have watched every Blade die and I have catalogued every dragon burial mound in Skyrim with incomplete information and I have waited for someone capable of using what I know." He took off his spectacles, cleaned them on his robe with a small, habitual gesture. "I cannot go to Bleak Falls Barrow myself. The Thalmor will kill me in the open road. But the Dragonstone is there ΓÇö a map of every dragon grave in Skyrim. Without it we are fighting blind. Waiting for each dragon to find us rather than finding them first."

He put his spectacles back on.

"I need you to go to Bleak Falls Barrow. I need you to bring me the Dragonstone. And I need you to understand that without it, everything else we might do is a reaction. Not a strategy."

He looked at the bodies visible through the open door ΓÇö the Thalmor kill squad, sprawled in the dark water of the corridor where the party had left them.

"They found me," he said. "This room is compromised. I cannot stay here."

He stood. He began, with the practiced efficiency of a man who had thought about this moment for decades, to identify which books were irreplaceable and which could be left behind.

"I will need somewhere to go," he said. "And you will need a Dragon Cult expert. That is what I am. Thirty years of preparation for this exact situation. I intend to use it."

He fit three books under his arm, tucked the letter inside his robe, and looked at the party.

"Shall we go up?"

