PART IX: THE SURFACE

Bjorn

The grate clanged shut behind them. Autumn air hit their lungs ΓÇö crisp, real, the smell of wood smoke and canal water. After the blood and stagnant dark of the Ratway it felt almost aggressive.

Esbern blinked rapidly, his head moving in small, orienting arcs. Thirty years. The light, even the late-afternoon amber of Riften's autumn, was information his eyes were still learning to process.

Mila's grip on Saijah's hand tightened. Open sky. She had never seen open sky. Not truly ΓÇö not without the platforms and walkways of the marketplace layered above her, not without a ceiling of city infrastructure filtering the light into something manageable. The sky was enormous. She pressed herself against Saijah's side and looked straight up and did not say anything.

Near the canal bridge, the cart was parked. Mable was being brushed in long, methodical strokes. Bjorn heard the grate close and turned around with a smile that had already begun to form before he understood what he was seeing.

Then his eyes found Mila.

The brush slipped out of his hand. It hit the cobblestones.

The smile was gone. The warmth was gone. The familiar weathered exasperation of a man who had spent his life surrounded by people who required more managing than they deserved ΓÇö all of it gone. What remained was still. Completely, chillingly still. The posture of his shoulders changed. The lines around his eyes pulled tight.

He walked toward them. Not shuffling. Not the careful amble of an old man with old joints. He moved with a liquid, unhurried precision that belonged to someone much younger and vastly more dangerous, and the party, who had seen him arm-wrestle a dwemer mechanism and survive a dragon's death-scream, had still never seen him move like this.

He stopped six feet away. His eyes were on the child. His voice was very low.

"Whose child is that."

Saijah started to answer. Alfonso said something. The explanation came out in pieces ΓÇö the Warrens, the mother, the skooma, the hundred gold, the transaction that had been framed as a rescue.

Bjorn listened without moving.

Then, quietly and completely, the dam broke.

"You *bought* her." Not a question. The words were flat with disbelief. "Like a sack of grain. Like a new sword."

He rounded on them ΓÇö not on one person but on all of them, his finger moving from face to face like an accusation that couldn't decide where to land.

"Look at yourselves. You are hunted by the Thalmor ΓÇö we just *confirmed* that. You are tracking Dragon Priests. You sleep in the dirt, you bleed every single day, and half of you aren't even human anymore."

His voice was rising. Not losing control ΓÇö rising with the specific, terrible clarity of a man who was right and had been right before and was furious that being right had never once made the outcome better.

"You didn't save her from the dark. You dragged her into the center of the apocalypse. What do you do when a dragon breathes fire on the cart? What do you do when a Justiciar puts a blade to her throat to make you drop your weapons? Who *feeds* her when you're underground fighting walking corpses?"

"She was safer with us thanΓÇö"

"*Safe.*" The word came out like a struck flint. "There is no safe within fifty miles of you. I have seen what happens when children get caught in the wake of people like us. They don't get adventures." A pause. The specific pause of a man choosing not to say something more specific. "They get butchered."

He looked at Mila. The explosive energy shifted ΓÇö not disappeared, shifted. He stepped forward and dropped to one knee in front of her, and the terrifying stillness became something else entirely. Fierce. Gentle. The desperation of a man who had crossed a continent of grief to arrive at this exact moment and was determined that this time it would go differently.

"What's your name, little one?"

"Mila," she whispered.

"Mila. I'm Bjorn. You're going to come sit on the cart with me, alright?"

He offered his hand. Mila looked at Saijah. Saijah, after a moment, nodded. The child took the old man's hand and let him lead her to the cart, and he settled her on the bench and wrapped Mable's spare blanket around her shoulders and pointed out a loose nail in the footboard that made an interesting sound if you pressed it just right. Mila pressed it. The nail made the sound. She pressed it again.

Bjorn stood up, turned back to the party, and pointed a calloused finger toward the center of the city.

"There is an orphanage three streets over. Honorhall. Safe walls, beds, a headmistress the whole city loves. We take her there, we give the woman a bag of gold to ensure she's fed, and we walk away."

The silence that answered him was the wrong kind of silence.

Orion spoke first. He had the intelligence from the Flagon ΓÇö the pipeline, the training rooms, the Guild's arrangement. He laid it out without embellishment: what Honorhall actually was, what Grelod actually did behind the grandmother's smile, what the orphans were actually being trained to become.

Bjorn listened. He was very still.

His face, as the picture assembled itself, underwent a change that none of them had seen before. Not anger ΓÇö the anger had already come and gone. Something older. The specific expression of a man who had spent forty years building a working model of the world in which there were places that were safe and people who were monstrous and the trick was knowing which was which. That model had just failed in a way he recognised.

A fine estate. A door he'd arrived at too late. A respectable man with a respectable reputation who had done things behind closed doors that respectable men weren't supposed to be capable of.

He had run for hours to reach that door. He had done everything right. He had still been two hours too late.

"There is nowhere to leave her," he said. The anger was gone. What remained was a weariness so old it had calcified into something structural. "Not the sewers. Not the orphanage. Not her mother."

He looked at Mila on the bench, pressing the loose nail with one finger, testing the sound of it.

"And not the open road," he said. "Not with us."

He breathed. A slow, ragged breath, the kind that carries weight.

"But we can't leave her here." He looked at each of them in turn. "She stays on the cart with me. You keep her out of your fights. You keep her out of the shadows."

His eyes moved to Orion. Stayed there for a moment. Whatever he saw in Orion's face ΓÇö the fangs, the ring, the careful professional blankness ΓÇö he filed under a heading and did not speak it aloud. Not yet.

"I stayed with you all because I believed you were better than the monsters I used to hunt," Bjorn said. "But if you let the darkness you carry spill over and catch her in the crossfire ΓÇö I will pack the cart, take her, and leave. And I won't ever come back."

He met their eyes. One at a time.

"Are we clear."

