PART X: THREE FIRES

The Couriers

The first arrived at the Bee and Barb the following afternoon.

A young Stormcloak soldier. Feverish. Pale. He had found them by asking for the Obsidian Lanterns at the gate and following directions inward, which told Davinia something about how far he had traveled and how long he had been sick while doing it. He was coughing into a rag that had been white when he left Windhelm. He found them at a corner table and he did not sit down because sitting down would have felt like giving up.

"Lady Caelus. General Stone-Fist sent me."

He told them what had happened. The march to Dawnstar. The medical supplies from Korvanjund ΓÇö from the tomb they had cleared, the supplies left behind, the ones that had gone north with Galmar's First Cohort as proof that the Lanterns were allies of the cause. The sickness starting on the march. Half the First Cohort dead in the snow before they drew swords. Vokun watching from the walls of Dawnstar as the Stormcloak army dismantled itself from the inside. The retreat. The plague following them home. Windhelm sealed. Ulfric behind closed doors in the Palace of the Kings while Galmar held the barricades alone.

"He said your magic was strong enough to hold back the walking dead at the tomb," the soldier said. "He begs you. If you have any honor left."

He left the words in the air between them and steadied himself against the table and waited.

None of them said anything for a moment. The plague the soldier was dying of had been mixed in those supplies at Korvanjund, in the dark, by Alfonso's hands, with precise and deliberate intent. The healers' restoration magic making it spread faster was confirmation ΓÇö he had built a disease that weaponised the cure. The army was dying of exactly what they had made it die of, and Galmar Stone-Fist, who trusted Davinia because she had lied to him and he had believed the lie, was begging her to fix it.

Davinia looked at the soldier. She looked at the rag in his fist.

"We'll come," she said.

It was the only thing to say. It didn't make it clean.

Klimmek arrived on the third day. He didn't come looking for the Lanterns specifically ΓÇö he burst through the door of the Bee and Barb and addressed the room, because what had happened to him on the 7,000 Steps was the kind of thing that requires a room, not a corner conversation. He was a big man, Klimmek. A provisioner. He made the weekly climb to High Hrothgar with food and supplies for the Greybeards, because someone had to and he had been doing it long enough that it had become his thing in the way that tasks become things ΓÇö not because anyone asked him to but because he showed up and kept showing up.

He had gone up the mountain. He had not reached the monastery.

"The Waystones," he said, to whoever was listening. "They were bleeding. Black sap. Like the rot they say is in the deep forests, but on the sacred path. On the 7,000 Steps." He took a drink before he'd finished ordering it. "And men in grey robes. Not the Masters ΓÇö they don't come down that far. These had faces. Faces of horn and fire. And the air felt wrong. Like time wasΓÇö" He stopped. Shook his head. "I ran. All the way here. Someone has to warn someone."

Saijah felt it ΓÇö a violent, localized spike through the clean healthy root network of the Rift, directional, pointing southwest. The Throat of the World. She knew that signature. She had been tracking it since Thornheart Grove, through Solitude, through every dying gildergreen along every road they'd taken. The Dagon cult wasn't contained to the forests anymore. They were on the most sacred path in Skyrim, between the world and the sky, bleeding the stones.

Klimmek hadn't asked the Lanterns for anything. He was shouting into the room because he needed someone to know. But he looked at them when he was done ΓÇö at the name on the wall outside, at the people sitting underneath it ΓÇö with the expression of a man who has run to find the people responsible and found them already here.

