PART XI: THE BEE AND BARB

The Night

Bjorn found the bar at the back of the Bee and Barb after Mila had fallen asleep on the cart under three blankets and the spare oilskin and Mable's warm proximity. He had checked on her twice before allowing himself to come inside. He sat at the bar with the deliberate purposefulness of a man who had earned a drink and knew it.

Davinia found him there.

She didn't plan it. She had been walking without destination through the upper city, carrying the amulet nobody would deliver and the silence Ismara maintained like a held breath, and the lamplight through the Bee and Barb's window had found her the way light finds people who have nowhere else to go.

She sat beside him. He glanced at her. He said nothing. He ordered a second cup.

They sat for a while in the specific silence of two people who have been through enough together that silence doesn't require filling.

Bjorn drank. Set the cup down. Looked at the grain of the bar.

"I used to be fast," he said.

Davinia had seen the speed ΓÇö through Wizard Sight at Krosulhah, the doubled aura of a man carrying two dragon souls, the way his body moved at the gate when he'd first seen Mila. She had not mentioned it. She waited.

"Not fast the way young men are fast. Fast the way a thing that shouldn't be possible is possible." He turned the cup in his hands. "I found out when I was about your age. Younger, maybe. Running a supply route north of the Pale Pass. Something came out of the dark ΓÇö bandits, Forsworn, it doesn't matter what ΓÇö and I ran. Not away. Toward them. And I covered ground I shouldn't have been able to cover in the time I covered it, and when it was over I was standing among people who had stopped breathing and I was not."

He drank.

"I told myself it was fear. That fear makes you fast. It was easier."

He was quiet for a moment. Outside, through the thick timber walls, the canal moved. Someone laughed in the upper room. The fire in the hearth made its small, domestic sounds.

"I made a promise to two children," Bjorn said. "Sisters. Lylana and Anya. They were traveling alone ΓÇö lost, frightened, too young to be on that road. I found them and I said: I will see you safe. You have my word." He paused. "I meant it. I always meant it."

"A noble's hunting party found us on the road. The kind of party that knows it doesn't have to ask permission for what it wants. They took the girls. I was... persuaded to let them go. Persuaded with swords and numbers." A flat self-contempt in the word. Not performance. Something he'd had forty years to calcify. "I ran after them when the party moved on. I ran for hours. I was fast ΓÇö I was as fast as I've ever been ΓÇö and I arrived at the estate two hours after they did."

He set the cup down.

"Two hours was too long," he said. "What I found ΓÇö what the noble had done ΓÇö in two hoursΓÇö"

He stopped. The fire crackled. He did not say what the noble had done. He had told this story to himself enough times that he had worn the specific details down to smooth stone, and those details stayed inside him, and the outline was enough.

"I killed him," Bjorn said. "And everyone in the estate. With my hands. I was there until morning."

"Then I buried what I'd found. And I buried who I was. Moved to the Rift. Became a fisherman. Became an old man with a cart. Became Bjorn." He looked at his hands on the bar. "I have spent forty years becoming a person. I am mostly a person now."

He glanced at Davinia.

"You have Wizard Sight. I know you've seen something when you look at me. I know it's been there since Krosulhah." A pause. "I'm not asking. I'm telling you that I know you know, and that it doesn't need to be said aloud."

Davinia looked at the bar. At the cup in front of her that she hadn't touched.

"Why are you telling me this?" she asked.

"Because you saw me look at that girl," Bjorn said. "When we came up from the Ratway. You saw what happened to my face. And you're smart enough to know that wasn't just a man worried about a child's safety."

He poured himself another cup.

"And because Kyboh is gone," he said. "And I had started to think of him as mine. The way you start to think of someone as yours when they're reckless and loud and stupid and they remind you of who you were before you understood that being reckless and loud and stupid gets people killed."

He drank.

"He reminded me of myself when young. Before the Pale Pass. Before I learned what fast was for." He shook his head. "And then the machine took him, and I wasn't there, and I couldn't run fast enough to change it because I wasn't even in the right building when it happened."

He turned to look at her directly.

"We're going to get him back," Bjorn said. It wasn't a question. It was the specific inflection of a man who had failed to say these words once before and had spent forty years understanding the cost.

Davinia looked at him. She thought about the amulet in her cloak. About the wedding hall and the six points and the door cracked to the width of a paw print. About the list in the Thalmor dispatch case and her father's name in the subtext of every line of it. About the Crown's silence, which had stopped feeling like restraint and started feeling like something that watched her think and kept its opinions to itself because it had decided, for reasons she didn't fully understand, that watching her think was more useful than directing her.

"We're going to get him back," she said.

The fire burned. The canal moved outside. They sat together in the way that people who have nothing left to perform sit together ΓÇö the warmth of proximity without the burden of it, two people with old damage and new losses, sharing the specific silence of those who have run at things they couldn't outrun and arrived too late and kept moving anyway.

At the bar of the Bee and Barb, in a city that had saved itself without them, the Obsidian Lanterns sat with their carter and did not speak about the things that mattered and understood each other perfectly.

